Some repentant Boko Haram terrorists and family members who recently surrendered to troops in Niger Republic have arrived Maiduguri, the Borno State capital. They arrived at the Maiduguri International Airport yesterday in a military aircraft in the company of soldiers led by Major General Bamidele Shafa, the coordinator of the “Operation Safe Corridor” programme initiated by the federal government for surrenderd Boko Haram terrorists. Major General Shafa who delivered 25 of the returnees comprising men, women, and children, said the repentant Boko Haram members laid down arms and surrendered to the Nigerien government, who contacted the Nigerian government to take them home. He said  the  Army have brought them home safely and handed them to the Borno State government for onward rehabilitation as part of the Operation Safe Corridor de-radicalization programme. The coordinator, Operation Safe Corridor said, “We are using this opportunity to encourage those that are still in the bush to come out because the president of the Federal Republic has given them an open arm to drop their weapons and embrace peace.” Recieving the returnees, the Borno State commissioner for Women Affairs and Social  Development, Hajiya Zoura Gambo, said the state government will provide them with psychosocial support, feed them, clothe them, and give some form of education and skills acquisition. She further said that a centre had been equipped by the Borno state governor, Professor Babagana Umara Zulum, with skills acquisition tools that will enable them to gain skills before they are reunited with their families. 